🧠 OS Concept 1: Page Replacement Algorithms
1️⃣ Simple Idea

When RAM is full and a new page comes:

👉 OS must decide which page to remove

That decision = Page Replacement Algorithm

🧠 Real-World Analogy

Imagine your bag 🎒 is full.

You need to add a new book.

You must remove one:

oldest book?
least used?
random?

That decision = algorithm

⚙️ Why It Exists

RAM is limited:

Pages > Frames

So replacement is necessary.

⚙️ Important Algorithms
1️⃣ FIFO (First In First Out)

👉 Remove oldest page

[1,2,3] → remove 1

❌ Problem: may remove useful page

2️⃣ LRU (Least Recently Used) 🔥

👉 Remove least recently used page

✔ Smart
✔ Most asked

3️⃣ Optimal (Best but theoretical)

👉 Remove page not used for longest future

✔ Best performance
❌ Not practical (future unknown)

🔗 Connection to Cache (Day 5)

Cache also uses similar logic:

👉 replacement policies

🎯 Placement Question

Q: Which page replacement algorithm is best?

👉 Optimal (theoretical), LRU (practical)

🧠 Memory Trick
FIFO = oldest out
LRU = least used out
🧠 OS Concept 2: Thrashing
1️⃣ Simple Idea

Thrashing =
👉 system spends more time swapping pages than executing

🧠 Real-World Analogy

Studying but constantly:

switching books
not actually learning

👉 zero productivity

⚙️ Why It Happens

When:

Too many processes
Too little memory
⚙️ What Happens
Page fault ↑
CPU utilization ↓
System slow
🔗 Connection to Paging

Thrashing occurs due to:

👉 excessive paging

🎯 Placement Question

Q: What is thrashing?

👉 High paging activity leading to low CPU utilization.

🧠 Memory Trick
Thrashing = working hard, achieving nothing
⚙️ COA Concept 3: I/O Organization
1️⃣ Simple Idea

I/O =
👉 communication between CPU and devices

Devices:

keyboard
mouse
disk
printer
🧠 Real-World Analogy

Manager talking to workers 🧑‍💼

CPU = manager
Devices = workers
⚙️ Methods of I/O
1️⃣ Programmed I/O

CPU checks device continuously

"Are you done?"
"Are you done?"

❌ Waste of CPU

2️⃣ Interrupt Driven I/O

Device interrupts CPU when done

✔ Efficient

3️⃣ DMA (Next topic)

👉 Direct transfer

🔗 Connection to Interrupts (Day 6)

Interrupt I/O uses:

👉 interrupts

🎯 Placement Question

Q: Why interrupt I/O is better than programmed I/O?

👉 CPU does not waste time waiting.

🧠 Memory Trick
Programmed = CPU waits
Interrupt = Device informs
⚙️ COA Concept 4: DMA (Direct Memory Access)

🔥 VERY IMPORTANT

1️⃣ Simple Idea

DMA =
👉 devices transfer data directly to memory without CPU

🧠 Real-World Analogy

Instead of boss doing all work:

👉 assigns work directly to worker

Boss = CPU
Worker = DMA controller

⚙️ Without DMA
Device → CPU → Memory

CPU busy ❌

⚙️ With DMA
Device → Memory (direct)

CPU free ✔

⚙️ How It Works

1️⃣ CPU gives instruction
2️⃣ DMA handles transfer
3️⃣ DMA sends interrupt when done

🔗 Connection to I/O

DMA improves:

👉 I/O performance

🎯 Placement Question

Q: What is DMA?

👉 Technique where data transfer happens directly between device and memory without CPU involvement.

🧠 Memory Trick
DMA = Direct Memory Access (no CPU)
